    "name": "Global variance-based sensitivity analysis for CFD hemolysis QoI",
    "description": "A Sobol variance-based global sensitivity analysis was conducted over a 500-sample quasi-random (Saltelli) ensemble spanning all eight uncertain input parameters within the operating envelope: flow rate Q, rotational speed N, blade clearance gap g, hematocrit Hct, blood viscosity mu, inlet turbulence intensity I_t, power-law hemolysis model exponent alpha, and mesh refinement level. The primary quantity of interest was the normalised index of haemolysis (NIH) at the pump outlet. First-order Sobol indices identified rotational speed N (S1 = 0.41) and blade clearance gap g (S1 = 0.29) as dominant contributors to NIH variance, together accounting for 70% of total output variance. Total-order indices confirmed negligible higher-order interactions (S_T - S1 < 0.05 for all factors). The hemolysis model exponent alpha contributed S1 = 0.17, motivating targeted experimental calibration reported in ValidationResult VR-04.",
    "method": "Sobol variance-based global sensitivity analysis (Saltelli sampling, 500 model evaluations)",
